[4] Israel: cases in children
Date: Wed 8 Sep 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/09/study-says-alpha-variant-doubled-covid-cases-israeli-kids


The SARS-CoV-2 alpha (B117) variant spread faster and more efficiently than previous strains among children 9 years and younger in Israel in late 2020 and early 2021, even amid the concurrent immunization of adults against COVID-19, according to an observational study yesterday [7 Sep 2021] in JAMA Network Open (https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamanetworkopen/fullarticle/2783851).

A team led by a researcher at Schneider Children's Medical Center of Israel in Petah Tikva compared the publicly available daily data of 21 615 children who tested positive for COVID-19 from 1 Aug to 2 Oct 2020 with those of 50 811 children who tested positive from 3 Dec 2020 to 3 Feb 2021. The researchers adjusted weekly incidence rates according to the number of COVID-19 tests performed.

Coronavirus transmission rates doubled -- but hospitalization rates dropped -- after alpha emerged in December 2020 and quickly unseated earlier strains as the dominant virus. The same scenario occurred in adults, with increased contagiousness but not severity. As Israel rolled out COVID-19 vaccines to adults, alpha came to account for 80% of cases.

The slopes of weekly adjusted incidence curves for children younger than 9 years were significantly higher in December 2020 to February 2021 than those in August to October 2020 (84.4 vs 39.1). The rate ratio (RR) of highest to lowest weekly incidence was also higher in the latter period (6.75 vs 3.62).

From December 2020 to April 2021, 15.7% of secondary cases identified through contact tracing involved children 9 years and younger (RR, 2.24) compared with 7.5% from February to November 2020.

A total of 0.98% of children who tested positive for COVID-19 from August to October 2020 were hospitalized compared with 0.52% during December 2020 to February 2021 (RR, 0.53). However, the percentage of hospitalized children who became severely ill or died was similar in both periods (6.5% in the earlier period and 6.9% in the latter; RR, 0.99).

Israel went into lockdown twice over the study period, from 18 Sep to 13 Oct 2020 and from 8 Jan to 7 Feb 2021. Schools closed from 14 Sep to 1 Nov 2020 and from 8 Jan to 15 Feb 2021. The country's COVID-19 immunization effort began on 20 Dec 2020, vaccinating 57% of adults with the 1st dose of the Pfizer/BioNTech vaccine by 3 Feb 2021.

The researchers noted that the rapid spread of alpha despite the expected mitigating effect of mass vaccination of adults in Israel underscores the importance of making COVID-19 vaccine available for young children. "Nonpharmacologic measures such as lockdown and school closure could not account for the difference in transmission since they were used during both periods," they wrote.

While the authors acknowledged that factors other than alpha may have contributed to the rapid coronavirus spread, they urged action to protect children. "These findings suggest that health authorities in different regions should anticipate this occurrence and implement measures to reduce spread in young children both in schools and at home," they wrote.

[Byline: Mary Van Beusekom]

